<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
A confused Ligius stepped into the chamber, overwhelmed by senses of familiarity, mystery, and fear. He knew not what lay in this chamber but for his premonition that it was both ancient and very important. Instinctively, Ligius reached for Requiem, shuddering as he realized that it was no longer at his side.<br>
        “What is this?” he could be heard to whisper. He knew that the unearthing of this place had been coincidental. The sandstorm’s happening almost at the same time as the beginning of Ligius’ journey… he felt as though some fate had preordained for him to find this place. Whatever divine scheme it was that was now occurring, Ligius intuitively knew that what was to come next would be an integral part in it.<br>
         All too suddenly, there was an unmistakable sound; a long, labored inhalation from what was undoubtedly a gargantuan beast. As the unknown creature exhaled, lights exploded across the chamber, revealing a giant statue, obviously carved in the likeness of a god. Standing approximately 50 feet tall, it was truly a majestic sight, and seemed to only grow more immense in size as Ligius approached it. At the base of the armored caricature a chest was placed, inscribed with faded words of an ancient text. The script was illegible save for a single word: Aaumin. “Aaumin…” Ligius repeated, brushing his hand over the ancient engraving, “the fallen Elder God.”<br>
        “Correct, I am Aaumin,” boomed a sudden, echoing voice that encompassed all of the chamber yet obviously emanated from some point within the caricature's bulk. “I have summoned you here, for there is that which must now be revealed. There is much about you Ligius, of which even you are ignorant. You live your life, day in and day out, sworn to protect in the name of Rashavic. You toil in these mortal confines, with no reprieve in sight. Such devotion, young man. And for all this, for what does your patron god stand?”<br>
        “For that which is good,” replied Ligius, regaining his composure, “I act as his instrument of light, in the holy duty to cleanse the world of that which is corrupt and evil.”<br>
        “Interesting,” interrupted the statue, “You destroy that which is evil, you say. You kill it, with neither remorse nor pity. Such heartlessness has become a second nature. Now, you can deny this, but let it be known that I speak the truth: The taking of life is unconditionally and completely evil. It is not in any way shape or form a good deed under any circumstance. What would you say to that?”<br>
        “I would say that I had thought as much,” Ligius responded, raising his voice to match that of the avatar, “but at some point I simply stopped trying to understand, and gave in to faith. I assumed- I prayed- that at least the gods would tell the difference when all was said and done.”<br>
        “Well Ligius, you assumed right. So, answer me this. Has your service to Rashavic not greatly enhanced your ability to take life? As you must have felt before, you are His avatar. His prophet. His very essence flows through you in concentrations the likes of which nobody bound by a mortal soul has ever experienced. Can you explain, then, why the god of ’that which is good’ would infuse you with such an unmistakably evil gift?”<br>
        “Why…” began Liguis, taken aback, “because in this imperfect world, it is necessary to fight evil, even if evil must be used as the means toward the end.”<br>
        “There was a time I was the most worshipped god in the land,” began Aaumin, changing the topic of conversation, “I was looked at as the embodiment of many things: knowledge, power, and chiefly: justice. Some were right- I am the God of Justice. These primitive peoples saw firsthand the atrocities of evil, and had need of a god which could fight this in kind. My disciples ruled with a fair but firm hand, Ligius, and the land prospered. Then, however, came the Renaissance. People softened, far removed from their id. Romantic philosophy evolved, and what I embodied was looked upon as an archaic and inherently cruel institution. The philosophies that my disciples held sacred were defiled and spat upon by the common man. Within a passing moment of time, my following was all but extinct. In place of justice, the newer man opted for a god of good… of truth… of righteousness. And, when you think about it, there is not much difference between what I was and what Rashavic became. However, the people did not see it as so. I was the fastest god to rise, and the fastest to fall. My worshippers abandoned me, Ligius. Do you know what happens to a god without worshippers?”<br>
        “Of course,” responded Ligius, “they die. Gods without worshippers cease to exist, for it is from the belief of mortals that gods derive their very essence, and thereby, their power.”<br>
        “Correct again, Ligius,” continued the avatar, “but then the question begs asking. My followers left me long ago. I am a dead god, Ligius. Yet I live. Did I defy the very laws that hold this universe together, or did I never die at all? Maybe, I just… changed. Think upon this Ligius, and realize what has come to pass. This bond that you feel now, tugging at your very soul, does it make this all clear now?        <br>
“It is becoming so, Aaumin, but continue.”<br>
        “Ahh, good. Patience, Ligius, was a quality that I valued highly among all my disciples. No coincidence at all. Now, bring forth your blade.” Ligius reached over his back, clasping the hilt of his greatsword. As the eerily radiant blade caught the light, the statue continued. “To kill, while an evil deed, does not make an evil person. Like you said, in this imperfect world, the ends must justify the means, unfortunately. You yourself have left uncountable corpses in your wake, yet you still can be held up as a beacon of good to the common man. However, your spirit does not go unblemished. While you remain a good man, you will, as a result of your tainted hand, be forever guilty. Such is the imperfection of justice as we know it. Now, think of the nature of your blade, Ligius. Many a good man hath died by Requiems blade… but never an innocent one.”<br>
        Understanding dawning on him, Ligius nevertheless remained quiet, staying attentive as Aaumin continued, obviously nearing the culmination of his speech. “Think of the nature of justice, that which I embody. In this world, justice is the practical man’s good. In of itself, justice is even inherently good. However, it requires a component of evil, which, while small, is absolutely crucial to its very essence. Justice, of course, has its validity derived from strictness, the threat of course being deeds that are undeniably evil. While good, justice allows for and even condones killing when such action is justified. Justice is all about fairness, about lawfulness, even righteousness. It is really not very much unalike your Temple of Rashavic. In fact, it is your Temple of Rashavic.”<br>
        “So, what you’re saying is…” stammered Ligius.<br>
        “That I am Rashavic. Or, that Rashavic doesn’t exist. Either way, I, Aaumin, am the entity that you up until now knew as your patron god. I never died because you, unknowingly of course, gave me my essence. It was the followers of Rashavic that worshipped me, albeit indirectly. However, as you now notice, even Rashavic’s following wanes. To counteract this, I made, for the first time in aeons, an avatar. I channeled my powers into one mortal, so as to give him potential unrivaled by that of any before him. That mortal is you, Ligius. From his birth, I tailored this mortal to be the perfect vessel of my power. The pain to which you were subjected, that which dehumanized you, which stripped you of even a basic capacity for love, this was all for a cause. The burning desire that was imbued within you, was put their for a reason by my hand! As my harbinger of justice, you would cleanse this world. People would see... and believe.”<br>
        “This all makes sense now,” said a suddenly tranquil Ligius. “While it relieves me to no end to know, for once, exactly who I am and where I belong, but still... If it is even possible, in light of these revelations I now know even less than before. Why now? Why did you pick now to tell me?”<br>
                &quot;That which is now unfolding... it requires you to act. Act sooner than I could have wanted, but not so soon that we are without hope. You can, and must, fulfill your potential.&quot;<br>
          &quot;How?&quot; asked Ligius, bewildered by what he heard.<br>
<br>
             “A simple question,” replied Aaumin, “and nearly as simple to answer. You simply must make the unwavering choice to accept your destiny. Not many people have the courage to accept such a heritage in face of the consequences. You, I sincerely hope and believe, do.”<br>
        “May I ask what these consequences are?” inquired Ligius, a definite note of uncertainty in his voice.<br>
        “Of course. Once you embrace your essence, there is no return. You are mortal, and will surely be overwhelmed. Your mind will take over, unrestrained by conscious thought. Now, seeing as to how conscious thought is what has kept your rage in check for so long, the consequences can and will be undeniably messy. The atrocities you might commit... they will damn you, and they will martyr you. You have no soul, only my essence. In its unrestrained release, this will become painfully apparent. Can you accept this fate?&quot;<br>
        “I… I think  I can,” replied Ligius, visibly shaken to the core.<br>
             “Good. I pray you can, and, as I said, I also believe you can. In the mean time, all I can ask is that you continue this journey. Ivan is dead, but not gone. The façade is now lifted and in this new light you will reach new heights of spirituality, and things will now, at last, just maybe, make sense. And, as a start, I can only suggest that you open the eyes of the Illuminous One. Cian was meant to know the truth.&quot; <p><img src=http://www.game-revolution.com/games/xbox/action/azurik_james.jpg>

